Difference between / and // in XPath

XPath me / aur // dono elements ko locate karne ke liye path specify karte hain, lekin inka meaning different hota hai.

Difference Table
Symbol	Meaning	Description
/	Direct child	Parent se direct child element locate karta hai
//	Anywhere in DOM	DOM me kahi bhi element search karta hai

-----------------
Single Slash /

/ ka use direct child element locate karne ke liye hota hai.

Example HTML:

<div>
   <form>
       <input id="username">
   </form>
</div>

XPath:
driver.findElement(By.xpath("/html/body/div/form/input"));

-----------------------------------
Double Slash //

// ka use DOM me kahi bhi element search karne ke liye hota hai.

Example:

driver.findElement(By.xpath("//input[@id='username']"));

➡️ Yeh DOM me kahi bhi username id wala input search karega.

Isliye automation me mostly // use hota hai.

Simple Example
/html/body/div/input   → using /

Exact path follow karta hai.

//input[@id='username']  → using //

Direct element search karta hai.

Interview Me Short Answer

Agar interviewer puche to aise bolo:

In XPath, / is used to locate a direct child element from the root,
while // is used to locate elements anywhere in the DOM regardless of their position.
